description: It's time to get the gang back together. The thing about reunion tours though, sometimes the band is a bit rusty, and takes a while for everyone to get back in rhythm. Old memories of past tours come up, old wounds. Some have healed all the way, others still bleed when scratched. But when that symphony of machine gun fire finds its rhythm again... the audience isn't going to know what hit them.

Enter the disconcerting world of Dominique Bertail, author of the series Ghost Money written by Thierry Smolderen. Period costumes, suits, military uniforms for Shandy, elegance remains the keyword. A real delight for the eyes! Then Bertail shows us his eclectic universe - landscapes, cowboys, portraits of comic books artists, tributes to Blueberry, Male Call, Thorgal, or Prince Valiant. With his precise lines and spare style, he can jump from one technique to another, from one world to another, from majestic to oppressive atmospheres. French text.

A gorgeous cartoon style, unrivaled fluidity, breathtaking dynamism, this is indeed the mark of the Italian artist Lorenzo De Felici, author of Drakka (Ankama). Through these pages, De Felici shares with the reader his remarkable and diversified world. Fantastic creatures emerge from murky waters, jumping monsters, challenging warriors, heroine fighting a dragon or afraid little girl. The 900 first copies are numbered and signed by the artist. French text.

The exceptionally talented Christian Rossi has worked with the best artists, from Charlier to Jijé and Moëbius. This sketchbook opens as an invitation to travel and highlights the spiritual dimension present in Rossi's work, his attraction for other shores and other peoples. His Live models sketches (pen, brush and ink) reveal the strenght and dynamism of his intense and generous lines. The 900 first copies are numbered and signed by the artist. French text.

The CIA has been trying for years to capture and use ghosts for espionage agents, but when a mysterious mercenary gets there first and attacks an assembly of NATO top brass, the race is on to find out how it was done and if it can be replicated before the mercenary and his spectral assassins strike again. Writer Joshua Starnes and artist Lisandro Estherren mix the thrills and street-level spycraft of The Bourne Identity with the ghostly terror of Poltergeist as top agent James Calley, racing across the US and Europe searching for answers, discovers the hunter is becoming the hunted.

The CIA gets a ghost agent of its own and quickly relearns the old adage about caution and wishes while Calley tries to make sense of his encounter with the entity that wiped out a NATO meeting. Writer Joshua Starnes and artist Lisandro Estherren bring another tale of thrilling spy adventure and chilling horror as the sinister agent behind the rash of poltergeists takes another step forward in his master plan.

Totally Blown Away

So there's a new lady in Knave's life now! Can she be everything she seems to be? And what of Knave's bizarre love rhombus with Abbie, Zoe, and Mark? How will the Knave survive?

Note: The digital edition (1/27/2016) for this issue was released before the print edition.

From Wes Craven, the legendary icon that changed the face of cinema, and Steve Niles (Writer of "30 Days of Night") comes the fourth chapter in Craven's original comic book series. Says Craven: "Ritchie's rise from idle ignorance to a young man/young vampire with a deep knowledge of the world, both the good and the bad, is fascinating to me. And that he finds his place, his mission to be something we can actually admire. He and his two friends will not be predators of the innocent. But they will be hunters - hunters of evil. And when they ferret it out they will do battle with it to the death, until the world is just a bit safer for the rest of us."

In celebration of Kochikame's 30th anniversary, many crossover tributes were made with other Shonen Jump series', past and present. Though this issue is dedicated to his crossing over into other current titles, a special issue Cho Kochikame was also released to feature other works crossing over (that is the comic advertised in the top right corner of this issue).

Most of Ryotsu's cameos in the series' published in this issue were in posters, magazines or calendars in the background, while a select few series featured him as a present character in crowd shots and a few even wrote him very specifically into their story.
